content:
Creating an HTML/CSS page with a `div` that contains three columns, each with a different background color, is quite straightforward. Here's a simple example to help you get started:

### HTML:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Three Columns Layout</title>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="styles.css">
</head>
<body>
    <div class="container">
        <div class="column column1">Column 1</div>
        <div class="column column2">Column 2</div>
        <div class="column column3">Column 3</div>
    </div>
</body>
</html>
```

### CSS (styles.css):

```css
body {
    font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
    margin: 0;
    padding: 0;
    display: flex;
    justify-content: center;
    align-items: center;
    height: 100vh;
    background-color: #f0f0f0;
}

.container {
    display: flex;
    width: 80%;
    max-width: 1000px;
    border: 1px solid #ccc;
    box-shadow: 0 0 10px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1);
}

.column {
    flex: 1;
    padding: 20px;
    color: #fff;
    text-align: center;
    font-size: 1.2em;
}

.column1 {
    background-color: #f44336; /* Red */
}

.column2 {
    background-color: #4caf50; /* Green */
}

.column3 {
    background-color: #2196f3; /* Blue */
}
```

### Explanation:

- **HTML**:
  - The `div` with the class `container` is used to wrap the three columns.
  - Each column (`column1`, `column2`, `column3`) is a `div` within the container. They are styled individually in the CSS.

- **CSS**:
  - The `container` uses `display: flex;` to create a flexbox layout, which automatically arranges its children (the columns) in a row.
  - Each `.column` class is given `flex: 1;` to ensure equal width distribution among the columns.
  - Different background colors are applied to each column using their respective classes (`.column1`, `.column2`, `.column3`).

You can adjust the styles such as padding, font-size, and colors as needed. This setup will provide a responsive layout that adjusts to different screen sizes while maintaining the three-column structure.
